If the codebase has external consumers (unlikely in early dev), 
document the migration path.

## Example Documentation

```rust
/// A `Widget` is a renderable component.
///
/// Widgets render themselves into a [`Frame`] within a given [`Rect`].
/// The Frame provides access to:
///
/// - **buffer** - The cell grid for drawing
/// - **hit_grid** - Optional mouse hit testing (for interactive widgets)
/// - **cursor_position** - Cursor placement (for input widgets)
/// - **degradation** - Performance budget hints (for complex widgets)
///
/// # Simple Widgets
///
/// Most widgets only need buffer access:
///
/// ```rust
/// fn render(&self, area: Rect, frame: &mut Frame) {
///     let buf = &mut frame.buffer;
///     // Draw to buffer...
/// }
/// ```
///
/// # Interactive Widgets
///
/// Widgets that handle mouse clicks should register hit regions:
///
/// ```rust
/// fn render(&self, area: Rect, frame: &mut Frame) {
///     // Draw to buffer...
///     if let Some(hit_grid) = &mut frame.hit_grid {
///         hit_grid.register(area, self.hit_id);
///     }
/// }
/// ```
```

## Important

This is lower priority than the actual migration - do this AFTER
